{{listen |filename=Turkey in the Straw.ogg |title="Turkey in the Straw" |description="Turkey in the Straw" performed by the [[United States Air Force Band]] }} '''Bob Farrell''' was a New York City-based [[blackface]] [[minstrel show|minstrel singer]], best known for introducing the song "Zip Coon" at the [[Bowery Theatre]] in 1834,<ref>{{cite book |author = Chase, Gilbert |isbn = 0-252-00454-X |publisher = University of Illinois Press |title = America's Music: From the Pilgrims to the Present |year = 2000 |page = 234}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Great Men of American Popular Song: The History of the American Popular Song|first=David|last=Ewen|year=1972|publisher=Prentice-Hall|isbn=0-13-364182-1 |page=23}}</ref> which later gave the tune to "[[Turkey in the Straw]]", one of the most famous and widespread songs of the era. "Zip Coon"'s authorship is disputed with [[George Washington Dixon]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Americana Song Reader|first=William E.|last=Studwell|year=1997|publisher=Haworth Press|isbn=0-7890-0150-0|page=58}}</ref>
